Introduction
============
Let

- :math:`\Omega` be the interior of one torus (:math:`k=1`) or two nested tori (:math:`k=2`),
- :math:`\Gamma := \partial \Omega`,
- :math:`\mathbf{n}` the outward unit normal to :math:`\Omega`,
- :math:`S_k` a cross-section of :math:`\Omega`,
- :math:`\lambda \geq 0`, and
- :math:`\Phi_k \in \mathbb{R}` for each :math:`k`.
  
``fmm-taylor`` is a MATLAB code that solves the boundary-value problem (BVP)

.. math::
   \begin{align}
   \nabla \times \mathbf{B} &= \lambda \mathbf{B} \ \text{in} \ \Omega \\
   \mathbf{B} \cdot \mathbf{n} &= 0 \ \text{on} \ \Gamma \\
   \oint_{S_k} \mathbf{B} \cdot \, \text{d}\mathbf{a} &= \Phi_k.
   \end{align}

Here :math:`\mathbf{B}` is the magnetic field and :math:`\Phi_k` is the magnetic flux through :math:`S_k`. A magnetic field c

This BVP arises when computing magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) equilibrium according to the multi-region relaxed MHD model

